","1437–1499":"1437–1499","1419–1490":"1419–1490","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","about 1437":"about 1437","1499":"1499","Abt 1442":"about 1442","1442":"1442","abt 1490":"about 1490","abt 1419":"about 1419","1419":"1419","1490":"1490","1407":"1407","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Swinden, Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Swinden, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Swinden, Yorkshire, England":"Swinden, Yorkshire, England","Banastre, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lancaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Cecilia de Lancaster was born about 1419, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thurstan de Banastre V in 1436, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1490, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 73."},"et":{"abt 1419–abt 1490":"umbes 1419–umbes 1490","1407–1442":"1407–1442","1437–1499":"1437–1499","1419–1490":"1419–1490","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","about 1437":"umbes 1437","1499":"1499","Abt 1442":"umbes 1442","1442":"1442","abt 1490":"umbes 1490","abt 1419":"umbes 1419","1419":"1419","1490":"1490","1407":"1407","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Swinden, Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Swinden, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swinden, Yorkshire, England":"Swinden, Yorkshire, England","Banastre, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"abt 1419–abt 1490":"noin 1419–noin 1490","1407–1442":"1407–1442","1437–1499":"1437–1499","1419–1490":"1419–1490","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","about